442
00:37:47,701 --> 00:37:56,692
He still gets up and he feels hungry and he puts his robe on and he picks up his bowl and he goes off and goes for an answer.

443
00:37:56,711 --> 00:37:57,552
Or he teaches.

444
00:37:57,612 --> 00:37:58,574
So he's always acting.

445
00:37:58,614 --> 00:38:03,159
In fact, occasionally he would go off by himself.

446
00:38:03,179 --> 00:38:05,161
He says for his own delight, his own

447
00:38:05,463 --> 00:38:08,166
and as an example to others.

448
00:38:08,585 --> 00:38:11,289
But he seems to have led a very active life.

449
00:38:12,030 --> 00:38:14,552
I mean, you know, he was on call, on tap.

450
00:38:14,612 --> 00:38:15,793
He was always walking everywhere.

451
00:38:16,153 --> 00:38:17,295
He spent many a time.

452
00:38:18,217 --> 00:38:22,260
We know where he spent his rainy seasons.

453
00:38:22,280 --> 00:38:28,608
They tended to be between the two kingdoms of Magadha and, what's the other one called?

454
00:38:29,188 --> 00:38:30,929
Anyway, the two main kingdoms there.

455
00:38:32,597 --> 00:38:36,585
So he was acting, but somehow they weren't wholesome or unwholesome.

456
00:38:38,108 --> 00:38:42,255
And all that's saying is that there's no self, it's not self-serving.

457
00:38:43,016 --> 00:38:45,541
Even when we do something wholesome, there's a bit of self-service.

458
00:38:46,123 --> 00:38:56,461
But when there's no sense of serving this imaginary self, and you are, as it were, in a direct, spontaneous communication,

459
00:38:57,606 --> 00:39:02,771
you know, with the people and nature around you and the world around you.

460
00:39:03,472 --> 00:39:10,559
And you see yourself as simply part of the flow of energies which are moving from one person to the other.

461
00:39:11,179 --> 00:39:16,244
And all you're doing through your understanding is helping the flow of goodness along.

462
00:39:17,626 --> 00:39:18,887
See what I mean?

463
00:39:18,907 --> 00:39:23,012
There's nothing there which attaches and says, oh, this is me or this is not.

464
00:39:23,032 --> 00:39:23,431
I am.

465
00:39:23,452 --> 00:39:26,635
I am finishing it off with, you know, I'm a,

466
00:39:27,003 --> 00:39:28,824
I am teaching, I am this and that.

467
00:39:28,844 --> 00:39:39,376
It's just that, there's just that interconnection, a contingency, which happens spontaneously to somebody who's liberated.

468
00:39:39,416 --> 00:39:42,739
And for us, what we do is we just create little barriers, that's all.

469
00:39:43,519 --> 00:39:44,842
And stop the flow of energy.

470
00:39:45,021 --> 00:39:46,784
We draw it back into ourselves, for me.

471
00:39:53,210 --> 00:39:55,913
So it doesn't, that's the whole thing about

472
00:39:58,559 --> 00:40:27,722
taking on the form of a human being is that it becomes a vehicle of expression whether it's negative or positive or in this sense neither negative nor positive see what I mean so it doesn't the process of liberation doesn't stop you from acting it just makes the acts more and more in

473
00:40:28,427 --> 00:40:31,052
Direct communication with the way things really are.

474
00:40:32,173 --> 00:40:39,105
Not being perverted by self-regard.

475
00:40:42,010 --> 00:40:44,873
Having said that, it's not as though the Buddha didn't take care of his body.

476
00:40:45,094 --> 00:40:52,726
So brushing your teeth is not... Yeah, brushing your teeth.

477
00:40:52,827 --> 00:40:56,072
It's not the same meaning you're serving the self.

478
00:40:56,152 --> 00:40:56,413
No.

479
00:40:56,773 --> 00:40:59,856
Yeah, you're taking care of your teeth.

480
00:41:02,679 --> 00:41:04,561
And considering they're the last lot we're going to have.

481
00:41:08,846 --> 00:41:10,106
So it is.

482
00:41:11,027 --> 00:41:12,550
Yeah, that's about it really.

483
00:41:14,771 --> 00:41:15,472
I'm just trying to think.

484
00:41:18,295 --> 00:41:25,282
I was also thinking of wording it as something like conventionally, day to day, we tend to think about meaning and

485
00:41:26,764 --> 00:41:29,748
I'm dedicating myself to X.

486
00:41:29,768 --> 00:41:30,949
That's right.

487
00:41:30,969 --> 00:41:45,621
But if that sense of meaning is dissolving, I think Adyashanti says that meaning is just another thing that the ego looks for, which is a very kind of shocking statement in a way.

488
00:41:49,806 --> 00:41:50,485
It depends.

489
00:41:50,927 --> 00:41:53,509
It depends.

490
00:41:53,548 --> 00:41:56,771
It's all to do with who the meaning is for

491
00:41:57,510 --> 00:42:08,288
So if it makes me feel bigger and better and me feel stronger and more powerful, then it's obviously a meaning which is corrupting me.

492
00:42:09,530 --> 00:42:20,447
But if the meaning of my life is for the benefit of others flowing outwards, then I'm at the service.

493
00:42:20,900 --> 00:42:27,226
To give oneself to a service you must let go of yourself because you're at the demands of other people.

494
00:42:28,108 --> 00:42:32,514
So it's not that you forget your own needs but you're out there for other people.

495
00:42:32,574 --> 00:42:37,159
I mean that's the whole point of seeing service as a way of completely getting rid of the self.

496
00:42:38,460 --> 00:42:49,253
In Zen understanding the best place to be is in the kitchen as a cook because there you have to feed all these different monastics

497
00:42:49,621 --> 00:42:52,344
And be aware of their little peculiar diets and what not.

498
00:42:52,364 --> 00:42:53,204
And make sure the food.

499
00:42:53,465 --> 00:42:55,146
And it's always for them, for them, for them.

500
00:42:55,487 --> 00:42:56,007
You eat.

501
00:42:56,789 --> 00:42:58,690
But you're actually doing it for them.

502
00:42:59,391 --> 00:43:01,233
So there's that sense of service.

503
00:43:01,253 --> 00:43:02,835
And that completely undermines.

504
00:43:03,496 --> 00:43:04,157
The ego.

505
00:43:04,177 --> 00:43:05,797
I don't like using that word.

506
00:43:05,818 --> 00:43:06,259
The self.

507
00:43:06,579 --> 00:43:08,842
Which is always thinking about itself.

508
00:43:09,402 --> 00:43:09,682
See.

509
00:43:09,762 --> 00:43:10,023
So.

510
00:43:10,063 --> 00:43:11,985
You know.

511
00:43:12,726 --> 00:43:13,527
I mean if I get.

512
00:43:13,907 --> 00:43:14,967
If somebody say.

513
00:43:15,708 --> 00:43:16,510
Wants an interview.

514
00:43:16,951 --> 00:43:19,273
When I'm happily engaged in this book.

515
00:43:19,657 --> 00:43:49,327
and I said oh bloody hell I've lost my sense of service my sense of service should be spontaneous as soon as somebody asks I'm out because that's what I've said I'm teaching now that doesn't mean to say that when I go on a personal retreat that I have to respond to that because then I'm looking after myself but as soon as I feel I've put myself out into the arena as a Dharma teacher then if any negativity comes up

516
00:43:49,882 --> 00:43:57,289
when I'm being asked to respond and that shows my sense of service is not yet purified.

517
00:43:57,349 --> 00:44:19,753
Now, the peculiar thing is that the more you give yourself to others or the more you give yourself to others, not forgetting one's needs as it were,

518
00:44:20,492 --> 00:44:22,635
the more the sense of self disappears.

519
00:44:24,177 --> 00:44:27,260
And the more the sense of meaningfulness grows.

520
00:44:27,280 --> 00:44:28,240
I mean, that's your paradox.

521
00:44:31,025 --> 00:44:44,239
Our sense of meaningfulness, the measure of our meaningfulness is the measure of our commitment to something greater than ourselves.

522
00:44:50,007 --> 00:44:56,976
And it's interesting that the Buddha would say things like, who sees the Dharma sees me, who sees me sees the Dharma.

523
00:44:56,996 --> 00:45:02,744
So he had this tremendous respect for the Dharma, for the way things are.

524
00:45:03,965 --> 00:45:05,407
And he serviced it completely.

525
00:45:07,590 --> 00:45:09,353
So that he could actually make that connection.

526
00:45:09,554 --> 00:45:12,438
Who sees me sees the Dharma in action.

527
00:45:13,358 --> 00:45:15,922
And who sees the Dharma also sees me.

528
00:45:15,963 --> 00:45:17,043
In other words, Buddha nature.

529
00:45:17,405 --> 00:45:19,827
How it ought to be.

530
00:45:21,563 --> 00:45:29,675
So I don't know, Adyashanti might have been thinking of it in that sort of more egotistic, more... Or storytelling-like.

531
00:45:30,596 --> 00:45:31,436
Yeah, maybe.

532
00:45:32,898 --> 00:45:40,811
But what you just said about authorship maybe helped me, because I had a very hard time when my book was published.

533
00:45:41,231 --> 00:45:46,338
Up to that point it was all about service, and then suddenly it became about me, my name.

534
00:45:46,588 --> 00:45:55,940
And it was devastating because I, you know, some of the interviews are about me and my skills and it was just awful, awful.

535
00:45:55,960 --> 00:46:00,965
Well, I don't think, yeah.

536
00:46:01,005 --> 00:46:02,086
Because, anyway.

537
00:46:02,967 --> 00:46:07,833
But even that, but you've got to be careful because remember there are three conceits, yeah.

538
00:46:07,853 --> 00:46:11,036
I am better than, which is of course the usual one, think of.

539
00:46:11,056 --> 00:46:11,797
But I'm worse than.

540
00:46:11,818 --> 00:46:14,300
See, that's a conceit.

541
00:46:16,052 --> 00:46:17,655
It's an inverted conceit isn't it?

542
00:46:17,675 --> 00:46:18,617
An inverted pride.

543
00:46:19,117 --> 00:46:21,780
And the subtle one is I am the same as.

544
00:46:22,961 --> 00:46:28,650
Because we group with people who are the same as us and other groups are either better or worse than us.

545
00:46:31,954 --> 00:46:35,739
Yeah.

546
00:46:36,161 --> 00:46:41,588
If when you were asked about your skills you had in mind

547
00:46:42,530 --> 00:46:46,833
just basically saying, this is how I did it.

548
00:46:49,235 --> 00:46:49,356
Right?

549
00:46:49,436 --> 00:46:51,237
I think that was my introduction.

550
00:46:51,257 --> 00:46:51,317
Eh?

551
00:46:51,336 --> 00:46:51,577
My foreword.

552
00:46:51,918 --> 00:46:52,998
Yeah.

553
00:46:53,018 --> 00:47:01,065
But what I mean is, it was all about me being a vehicle and being a servant to that subject.

554
00:47:01,085 --> 00:47:06,489
And then suddenly, the world puts the spotlight on you.

555
00:47:07,030 --> 00:47:08,931
And you think, no, why are you looking at me?

556
00:47:08,952 --> 00:47:09,472
Look at it.

557
00:47:10,472 --> 00:47:11,773
So that was a big disappointment.

558
00:47:12,275 --> 00:47:12,434
Ah.

559
00:47:14,018 --> 00:47:16,380
Well, we live in a society of celebrities.

560
00:47:18,802 --> 00:47:21,465
In the old days, you never put your name on work, did you?

561
00:47:21,525 --> 00:47:23,445
I need a pseudonym, I think.

562
00:47:23,465 --> 00:47:24,166
I need a pseudonym.

563
00:47:24,246 --> 00:47:29,532
I'm seriously considering one.

564
00:47:29,552 --> 00:47:33,335
It might be easy.

565
00:47:33,454 --> 00:47:36,338
Anyway, sorry if that was unnecessary.

566
00:47:36,358 --> 00:47:40,041
No, it's alright.

567
00:47:40,061 --> 00:47:41,021
Does that make sense a bit?

568
00:47:42,422 --> 00:47:42,523
Yeah.

569
00:47:45,018 --> 00:47:48,362
In the introductory talk, you used the words abiding in the present moment.

570
00:47:48,463 --> 00:47:55,213
It occurred to me, now this doesn't have the emotional punch, the Christian hymn, Abide With Me.

571
00:47:55,253 --> 00:48:01,443
How will Theravada ever make up the levels of emotional support that Christianity seems to offer?

572
00:48:02,985 --> 00:48:10,856
That reminds me of someone who used to, well, she would define herself, I think, or she would say of herself that she's a Buddhist.

573
00:48:11,630 --> 00:48:16,536
And she's a good meditator and she goes to Amarawati.

574
00:48:16,677 --> 00:48:18,739
But it was just too dry.

575
00:48:18,760 --> 00:48:23,688
She had to go along to a Christian church to get a bit of emotional oomph.

576
00:48:24,108 --> 00:48:33,402
I think there's a deficit in the way that

577
00:48:33,905 --> 00:49:03,050
Buddhism comes to the West and in the way it's taught and when you go to the East you see that there's no deficit on the emotional side and it's to do with the way that why we come to the practice we come to the practice really to sort out a lot of us to sort out our problems to understand the world etc etc and unwittingly we're not juicing it up with religious emotions and

578
00:49:03,858 --> 00:49:12,547
That was one of the things about the carol service, you see, to try and see these emotional supports.

579
00:49:13,628 --> 00:49:18,653
And as you point out, Christianity is excellent at doing that.

580
00:49:18,673 --> 00:49:21,637
The music is so moving.

581
00:49:21,898 --> 00:49:29,965
When my father died, I was in Sri Lanka at the time, and on hearing the news, I cried a little bit.

582
00:49:30,407 --> 00:49:32,329
But by the time I got back to my cootie,

583
00:49:32,646 --> 00:49:44,324
all that had gone, because I had a very good relationship with him, and he lived a good life, and I really was quite happy, you know, and he died very quickly, there was no lingering, you know.

584
00:49:46,085 --> 00:50:01,168
So I was fairly okay with it all, you know, and I was with my mother in the church ceremony, and there's this hymn, I can't quite remember it, but it's the love of Jesus, I can't bring it to mind, but

585
00:50:01,655 --> 00:50:05,139
As soon as it started, the tears are flowing down my face.

586
00:50:05,159 --> 00:50:09,443
It really cranked it up, just an astrology.

587
00:50:10,065 --> 00:50:15,030
So, music, as you know, is this tremendous power to, you know, raise.

588
00:50:15,050 --> 00:50:18,355
And there's not much of it in Theravada Buddhism.

589
00:50:18,375 --> 00:50:19,916
You know, you're just chanting.

590
00:50:20,898 --> 00:50:29,788
Now, an interesting, another little interesting aside is that there was a an Oxford, sorry, a

591
00:50:31,135 --> 00:50:59,842
an orthodox monk in London this is years and years ago who led a choir and he said it was so difficult to stop the choir singing emotionally and if you listen to plain chant it's not emotional in the sense that it comes out of silence it comes out of silence and

592
00:51:00,092 --> 00:51:07,844
In my humble opinion, ever since Plain Chant, there's been nothing but corruption.

593
00:51:07,864 --> 00:51:15,356
So, if you consider what are the emotional, what are spiritual emotions?

594
00:51:16,699 --> 00:51:20,364
And they're actually serviced in Theravada if you want to do the exercises.

595
00:51:21,326 --> 00:51:23,969
So the first one is a sense of gratitude.

596
00:51:24,871 --> 00:51:25,813
And by gratitude,

597
00:51:26,434 --> 00:51:36,889
just going through the Buddha's life and what he went through and what we've received from it, then every time you look at a Buddha statue, you just get this enormous gratitude.

598
00:51:37,369 --> 00:51:39,213
And that comes easy to Easterners.

599
00:51:40,675 --> 00:51:42,938
There's a sense of awe.

600
00:51:42,958 --> 00:51:45,280
A sense of, you know, when you realise what he achieved.

601
00:51:45,300 --> 00:51:48,846
And you realise the ineffability, really, of the Dharma.

602
00:51:48,985 --> 00:51:51,028
The whole thing, you know, like why we're here.

603
00:51:51,809 --> 00:51:53,952
All that is never really explained.

604
00:51:54,534 --> 00:51:56,255
You know, how is it we're here in the first place?

605
00:51:56,590 --> 00:52:25,855
you know, like, where does this Buddha nature, where's it arisen from, where's it, you know, like, there's a whole load of, of metaphysics, which is just, completely dark, and he never went into it, because, from his point of view, it would just be inference, all we can know, is what's within, this bubble of awareness, that we have, see, and then there's praise, you see, and that's where you get the, the joy, the wonderful joy, now, if anybody goes to,

606
00:52:26,492 --> 00:52:31,579
say one of the main shrines in Sri Lanka, or anywhere really, but the one I'm thinking of in Sri Lanka there.

607
00:52:32,820 --> 00:52:36,867
And you go along on a puja day, which is the full moon day of a month.

608
00:52:36,887 --> 00:52:38,088
That's the main one.

609
00:52:38,108 --> 00:52:40,672
I mean, you can slice the emotions like butter.

610
00:52:42,253 --> 00:52:47,820
And you can see people are completely, they're just up in that seventh heaven of emotional bliss.

611
00:52:49,523 --> 00:52:52,467
So in a sense, that's something that...

612
00:52:54,117 --> 00:53:05,847
perhaps comes, is instilled in you as a child, you know, and that as you move into adulthood and you haven't got that, which a lot of young people now don't have.

613
00:53:05,867 --> 00:53:11,853
I mean, they've got all the music stuff, but they don't have these subtle religious emotions.

614
00:53:11,873 --> 00:53:20,461
In my own case, I didn't really get into the emotional side of Buddhism until quite late.

615
00:53:21,067 --> 00:53:24,411
I would have been already 15 years or so practicing.

616
00:53:25,532 --> 00:53:37,246
And then slowly I began to see that there was a, I hadn't developed a heart relationship to the religion I had chosen.

617
00:53:38,086 --> 00:53:41,650
And as that came along, then I realized, you know, that's what I've got to do.

618
00:53:42,112 --> 00:53:46,257
And that's why I've got all these statues and Kuan Yin and a stupa.

619
00:53:46,737 --> 00:53:48,018
Because a stupa is a,

620
00:53:48,472 --> 00:53:51,554
is really a tombstone.

621
00:53:52,215 --> 00:53:52,856
That's what it is.

622
00:53:54,117 --> 00:53:57,820
It's their representative of the Buddha's life.

623
00:53:57,840 --> 00:54:05,248
And that's why I try to pop that, but not too much avail, I'm afraid.

624
00:54:05,268 --> 00:54:10,072
Because most people who come to the meditation really just want to sort themselves out.

625
00:54:10,092 --> 00:54:18,039
And I think that emotional value and the feeling of a heart connection with

626
00:54:18,322 --> 00:54:21,148
a religion we're in, grows in time.

627
00:54:23,851 --> 00:54:29,621
See, and having said that, you know, brought up a Catholic, I walk into a Catholic church, I'm in a certain event.

628
00:54:29,641 --> 00:54:34,108
I'm just back there, it's just beautiful, you know, just the feeling.

629
00:54:34,128 --> 00:54:41,579
I went to a, I think it would be a Tibetan Buddhist service with a friend of mine in Seattle.

630
00:54:41,601 --> 00:54:45,646
But they were doing singing, they were using, translated

631
00:54:46,150 --> 00:54:49,715
Tibetan texts, but to very westernized melodies.

632
00:54:50,356 --> 00:54:52,518
And that struck me as so artificial.

633
00:54:53,581 --> 00:54:56,864
It wasn't a pleasing... For me, it was not a pleasing solution.

634
00:54:57,847 --> 00:54:59,088
No sense of profundity.

635
00:54:59,108 --> 00:55:01,070
Yeah, it didn't have the...

636
00:55:01,090 --> 00:55:02,233
The profundity of the chant.

637
00:55:02,492 --> 00:55:04,476
Yeah.

638
00:55:04,496 --> 00:55:09,402
Or even the profundity of the western traditional... Yeah.

639
00:55:09,422 --> 00:55:10,965
It's very difficult, isn't it?

640
00:55:11,144 --> 00:55:12,967
I think Amarawati have done a decent job.

641
00:55:13,842 --> 00:55:18,387
if you listen to their chant, they still, they chant in the Pali and they're in English.

642
00:55:18,646 --> 00:55:19,547
And it's still a chant.

643
00:55:21,010 --> 00:55:22,791
And I think they, they do it nicely.

644
00:55:22,871 --> 00:55:25,355
People ask me, you know, why don't I do it here?

645
00:55:25,394 --> 00:55:31,862
But that takes, that takes, I need to know a musician and I need to, I mean, I'm happy with the Pali.

646
00:55:34,005 --> 00:55:34,706
Well, it's lovely.

647
00:55:35,085 --> 00:55:37,748
I thought the chant this morning, I really enjoyed it.

648
00:55:38,530 --> 00:55:39,130
That's right.

649
00:55:39,150 --> 00:55:40,271
You know, it just has a, you know,

650
00:55:42,782 --> 00:55:50,235
It's a Burmese, Burmese type chant.

651
00:55:50,255 --> 00:55:56,284
For about 10 days after I left the retreat, back in the summer, every night it kept ringing in my ears.

652
00:55:56,726 --> 00:55:58,108
And it turned into a lullaby.

653
00:55:58,369 --> 00:56:03,998
And it was incredibly soothing and comforting.

654
00:56:14,389 --> 00:56:19,978
So I do think that that's part of the process at some point.

655
00:56:19,998 --> 00:56:28,068
There has to be, I don't know about an emotional punch, but some heart connection.

656
00:56:28,590 --> 00:56:31,414
It becomes very dry.

657
00:56:31,434 --> 00:56:34,237
The other way people do it is through the practice of metta, of course.

658
00:56:34,257 --> 00:56:37,722
That's another way.

659
00:56:37,742 --> 00:56:39,786
There's a reason it's making me think.

660
00:56:39,806 --> 00:56:41,208
I can't remember who she is.

661
00:56:41,228 --> 00:56:42,809
A contemporary Christian mystic.

